68
00:08:22,335 --> 00:08:23,711
Come on, come on.

69
00:08:24,545 --> 00:08:26,547
Come on, baby.

70
00:08:29,509 --> 00:08:30,927
[ENGINE TURNS OVER]

71
00:08:31,093 --> 00:08:32,011
Yes.

72
00:08:38,184 --> 00:08:41,896
So come on down to Duke City Recliners,
and put your feet up.

73
00:08:42,063 --> 00:08:45,733
Mention this ad
and get 10 percent off your first purchase.

74
00:08:46,609 --> 00:08:48,486
And cut. Great.

75
00:08:48,653 --> 00:08:50,488
-How was that?
-Camera's good.

76
00:08:50,655 --> 00:08:52,073
Thank you. That was great.

77
00:08:52,240 --> 00:08:55,451
Hold up, hold up. I wanna do one more.

78
00:08:55,618 --> 00:08:56,911
Was that okay?

79
00:08:57,078 --> 00:08:58,079
It was great...

80
00:08:58,246 --> 00:09:03,334
...but I just--
I want you to connect more with the audience.

81
00:09:03,501 --> 00:09:05,670
Like you're talking to a friend.

82
00:09:06,379 --> 00:09:09,006
Look into that lens, and see a friend.

83
00:09:09,173 --> 00:09:10,174
Can you do that?

84
00:09:10,341 --> 00:09:12,426
I mean, think of a specific friend.

85
00:09:12,593 --> 00:09:14,387
-Do you see him?
-Yes.

86
00:09:14,554 --> 00:09:15,846
Okay, who is he?

87
00:09:16,013 --> 00:09:18,057
-My friend Ron.
-Great.

88
00:09:18,224 --> 00:09:20,893
Look into that lens, and see Ron.

89
00:09:21,060 --> 00:09:24,730
And just--
Two guys just chatting about chairs.

90
00:09:25,731 --> 00:09:29,944
Don't think about it. Just throw it away.
Last looks. Roll sound.

91
00:09:33,698 --> 00:09:35,866
-Sound speed.
-Camera set.

92
00:09:36,033 --> 00:09:37,493
And...

93
00:09:37,952 --> 00:09:40,329
...having a conversation
with your good friend Ron.

94
00:09:40,496 --> 00:09:42,123
Just a couple of guys talking.

95
00:09:42,290 --> 00:09:45,793
And you got some
very exciting news about the recliners...

96
00:09:45,960 --> 00:09:49,589
...that you've been dying to share with him,
and action.

97
00:09:49,755 --> 00:09:53,175
So come on down to Duke City Recliners,
and put your feet up.

98
00:09:53,342 --> 00:09:57,263
Mention this ad
and get 10 percent off your first purchase.

99
00:09:58,097 --> 00:10:00,099
And cut. Great. That's the one.

100
00:10:00,266 --> 00:10:03,477
-Check the gate. How'd that feel?
-Good, I guess. What did you think?

101
00:10:03,644 --> 00:10:07,273
Good. So good. Just very, very...

102
00:10:07,356 --> 00:10:08,733
-...great.
-Very nice.

103
00:10:08,899 --> 00:10:11,319
Listen. You are on a roll, my friend.

104
00:10:11,485 --> 00:10:15,114
I say we strike while the iron is hot.
Remember that other offer we discussed?

105
00:10:15,281 --> 00:10:17,450
More commercials at the discounted rate?

106
00:10:17,617 --> 00:10:20,786
Got my whole crew here.
We can bang out seven more...

107
00:10:20,953 --> 00:10:23,247
...and give you a run
that will make you a household name.

108
00:10:23,414 --> 00:10:26,334
-What do you say?
-Mr. Goodman, I...

109
00:10:26,500 --> 00:10:28,753
...love the idea of more commercials.

110
00:10:28,919 --> 00:10:32,006
But I just can't swing it.
My wife didn't want me to do this one.

111
00:10:32,173 --> 00:10:37,303
You know what? They say you gotta
spend money to make money, and, uh--

112
00:10:37,511 --> 00:10:38,596
[LAUGHS]

113
00:10:38,804 --> 00:10:43,517
And I tell you what, you got a chance here
to potentially spike your sales by hundreds--

114
00:10:43,684 --> 00:10:47,688
Hell, thousands of new customers who'd
never even heard of Duke City Recliners.

115
00:10:47,855 --> 00:10:48,898
What do you say?

116
00:10:49,106 --> 00:10:50,608
Sure, sure.

117
00:10:50,775 --> 00:10:52,568
But like I said...

118
00:10:52,735 --> 00:10:54,945
...I only have enough to pay for the one.

119
00:10:56,864 --> 00:10:58,741
Well, you know what?

120
00:10:59,575 --> 00:11:00,576
I like you.

121
00:11:00,743 --> 00:11:02,244
And I wanna help, so...

122
00:11:02,411 --> 00:11:06,499
...I know we discussed
a discounted rate of 545 per commercial...

123
00:11:06,666 --> 00:11:10,169
...but if you sign up right now
for our elite package...

124
00:11:10,336 --> 00:11:12,630
...now that's seven commercials...

125
00:11:12,797 --> 00:11:17,009
...I think we can do the whole thing
for 500 per commercial.

126
00:11:17,176 --> 00:11:21,722
Now that is 3500 all-in.
That is a bargain of a lifetime.

127
00:11:28,270 --> 00:11:29,563
I don't know.

128
00:11:31,023 --> 00:11:33,484
Any chance you can do it on credit?

129
00:11:35,528 --> 00:11:37,154
On credit?

130
00:11:37,863 --> 00:11:39,073
No.

131
00:11:39,698 --> 00:11:41,534
No. I can't.

132
00:11:41,951 --> 00:11:43,035
Sorry.

133
00:11:43,244 --> 00:11:44,620
Maybe another time?

134
00:11:44,787 --> 00:11:47,206
Let me get your money for this one.

135
00:11:58,217 --> 00:12:00,386
Can we make this easier
and split it four ways?

136
00:12:00,553 --> 00:12:04,181
I'll split you four ways. Don't they
teach you capitalism in that school?

137
00:12:04,348 --> 00:12:08,102
-I'm just saying we got expenses, man.
-You don't have expenses. I got expenses.

138
00:12:08,269 --> 00:12:11,647
You see this? This is money
I've spent on airtime for that commercial.

139
00:12:11,814 --> 00:12:14,567
Four hundred and forty-five bucks.
Know what that leaves me?

140
00:12:14,733 --> 00:12:17,820
-One hundred dollars.
-One hundred and four dollars and 95 cents.

141
00:12:17,987 --> 00:12:21,824
For writing, directing, producing,
client outreach, sales, transpo...

142
00:12:21,991 --> 00:12:23,200
-...all of it.
-I get it.

143
00:12:23,367 --> 00:12:25,953
So let's get you in the editing room
and finish this...

144
00:12:26,036 --> 00:12:27,955
...and I don't wanna hear about expenses.

145
00:12:28,497 --> 00:12:30,833
KIM:
Okay, electric.

146
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:32,585
I paid this month.

147
00:12:32,793 --> 00:12:34,503
Anything else?

148
00:12:34,795 --> 00:12:37,465
I bought a couple reams of paper
for the printer.

149
00:12:37,631 --> 00:12:40,301
Mm. Paper.

150
00:12:41,802 --> 00:12:45,764
One hundred and sixty-two. Okay. So....

151
00:12:48,309 --> 00:12:50,102
Um....

152
00:12:51,020 --> 00:12:52,062
Looks like...

153
00:12:52,229 --> 00:12:54,106
...puts me ahead this month...

154
00:12:54,273 --> 00:12:56,734
...$3,172.00.

155
00:12:57,818 --> 00:13:00,738
All right. What's it to even me up?

156
00:13:00,946 --> 00:13:02,948
Uh, divided by two.

157
00:13:03,115 --> 00:13:05,993
One thousand, five hundred, eighty-six.

158
00:13:07,077 --> 00:13:08,370
Okay.

159
00:13:08,537 --> 00:13:10,372
One thousand.

160
00:13:11,165 --> 00:13:12,791
Five hundred.

161
00:13:12,958 --> 00:13:15,836
Wow, Mr. Moneybags, huh?

162
00:13:16,003 --> 00:13:17,463
So this...

163
00:13:17,755 --> 00:13:19,965
...commercial thing, it's turning a profit?

164
00:13:20,174 --> 00:13:24,345
It's TV. How could there not be a profit?

165
00:13:27,765 --> 00:13:29,183
You didn't...

166
00:13:29,600 --> 00:13:31,936
...drain your bank account, did you?

167
00:13:32,144 --> 00:13:34,730
Heh. No. I didn't, no.

168
00:13:34,939 --> 00:13:36,023
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

169
00:13:36,232 --> 00:13:37,691
Oh, that's Chinese food.

170
00:13:37,858 --> 00:13:40,945
-I ordered it for us. You're working late?
-Yeah. Thanks.

171
00:13:41,111 --> 00:13:43,322
-Oh, uh, wait. Here.
-No.

172
00:13:43,489 --> 00:13:45,115
I got this.

173
00:13:48,744 --> 00:13:51,372
-Hey. Hi.
-Twenty-four dollars.

174
00:13:56,252 --> 00:13:57,503
Keep the change.

175
00:14:00,923 --> 00:14:02,007
A dollar?

176
00:14:02,216 --> 00:14:03,801
Yeah.

177
00:14:04,593 --> 00:14:06,470
We can make it zero.

178
00:14:08,847 --> 00:14:10,766
[DANCE MUSIC
PLAYING OVER CAR SPEAKERS]

179
00:14:27,283 --> 00:14:29,535
[ALARM SENSOR BEEPING]

180
00:14:41,547 --> 00:14:43,090
[BEEPING STOPS]

181
00:14:43,841 --> 00:14:45,092
[SCREAMS]

182
00:14:45,259 --> 00:14:46,302
Jesus.

183
00:14:46,468 --> 00:14:47,845
What the hell?

184
00:14:48,012 --> 00:14:50,264
I mean, what the hell? How'd you get in here?

185
00:14:50,973 --> 00:14:52,474
Relax.

186
00:14:52,892 --> 00:14:54,810
-I just wanna talk.
-Talk?

187
00:14:55,019 --> 00:14:57,313
Heh. You mean, like, apologize?

188
00:14:57,479 --> 00:14:59,899
Because that's really the only talk
I wanna hear.

189
00:15:00,816 --> 00:15:03,235
I wanna do some business like before.

190
00:15:03,444 --> 00:15:05,112
Heh. Business?

191
00:15:05,279 --> 00:15:08,741
Is that, like,
code for stealing my baseball cards?

192
00:15:08,908 --> 00:15:11,535
I'm not here for your baseball cards.

193
00:15:14,538 --> 00:15:16,040
I'm here...

194
00:15:16,206 --> 00:15:17,333
...for this.

195
00:15:27,009 --> 00:15:28,218
Can you get more of these?

196
00:15:38,812 --> 00:15:40,856
PRYCE:
You want me to steal this?

197
00:15:41,065 --> 00:15:43,275
Get a prescription and go to a pharmacist.

198
00:15:43,442 --> 00:15:46,570
-It'll be cheap.
-I need those capsules empty.

199
00:15:46,737 --> 00:15:48,572
Before they're sealed.

200
00:15:48,739 --> 00:15:51,033
With those exact markings.

201
00:15:54,828 --> 00:15:58,374
The place I work doesn't make these, but....

202
00:16:00,876 --> 00:16:02,044
"But" what?

203
00:16:05,130 --> 00:16:11,136
I could probably get some samples
diverted on an R & D request.

204
00:16:12,304 --> 00:16:13,514
So do it.

205
00:16:13,681 --> 00:16:15,641
Why? I mean, what's the point?

206
00:16:15,808 --> 00:16:17,476
I need them.

207
00:16:18,602 --> 00:16:20,354
Okay.

208
00:16:21,188 --> 00:16:24,608
And if I don't get them...

209
00:16:24,775 --> 00:16:25,776
...then what?

210
00:16:25,943 --> 00:16:27,444
Are you gonna...

211
00:16:27,611 --> 00:16:30,322
...threaten me? Break my legs?

212
00:16:33,075 --> 00:16:37,454
You get me those pills,
and I'm gonna pay you $20,000.

213
00:16:42,084 --> 00:16:43,585
Get them.

214
00:17:53,322 --> 00:17:54,615
Hey, Pop.

215
00:17:54,782 --> 00:17:56,366
You're doing okay?

216
00:17:56,909 --> 00:17:58,410
Yeah. It's coming along.

217
00:17:58,577 --> 00:18:00,996
I have a couple of volunteers here
who wanna help.

218
00:18:01,163 --> 00:18:02,790
Well, thanks, but I think I'm good.

219
00:18:02,956 --> 00:18:05,292
Please.
We can't let you do it all by yourself.

220
00:18:05,459 --> 00:18:07,961
Certainly not after you've bought
all the supplies.

221
00:18:08,128 --> 00:18:10,005
At least let the church reimburse you.

222
00:18:10,172 --> 00:18:11,298
It's a donation.

223
00:18:11,465 --> 00:18:16,011
Come on. You've got unskilled
but eager laborers. Let us do something.

224
00:18:16,178 --> 00:18:18,806
Just point and tell us what to do.

225
00:18:19,515 --> 00:18:20,933
Oh.

226
00:18:23,393 --> 00:18:25,020
All right. Uh....

227
00:18:27,189 --> 00:18:30,317
How about you dump one of those packs
into the wheel barrow?

228
00:18:30,484 --> 00:18:33,612
And you, you fill that bucket
up to the brim with water.

229
00:18:33,779 --> 00:18:35,906
And then you dump it in little by little...

230
00:18:36,073 --> 00:18:37,866
...while he stirs it with a hoe.

231
00:18:38,617 --> 00:18:40,494
-You got it.
-Okay.

232
00:18:45,624 --> 00:18:47,251
I'm ready. What can I do?

233
00:18:48,961 --> 00:18:50,963
I think we're covered.

234
00:18:51,130 --> 00:18:52,422
You're kidding, right?

235
00:18:52,589 --> 00:18:54,424
It's not that big a job.

236
00:19:06,145 --> 00:19:07,646
-Am I doing this right?
-Uh....

237
00:19:09,439 --> 00:19:11,733
Why don't you try using this instead?

238
00:19:13,944 --> 00:19:15,320
Excuse me.

239
00:19:15,529 --> 00:19:17,656
It's for the walkway.

240
00:19:17,823 --> 00:19:19,241
Look.

241
00:19:20,534 --> 00:19:22,619
It puts down a texture...

242
00:19:22,786 --> 00:19:25,122
...so the kids don't slip when it gets wet.

243
00:19:36,550 --> 00:19:38,010
Like this?

244
00:19:38,260 --> 00:19:39,845
You got it.

245
00:19:40,304 --> 00:19:41,346
Nice and gentle.

246
00:19:42,055 --> 00:19:45,100
ANITA: You're Kaylee's Pop-Pop, right?
-I am.

247
00:19:45,309 --> 00:19:47,811
I am the very proud grandfather.

248
00:19:48,979 --> 00:19:51,231
-I'm Anita.
-Mike.

249
00:19:51,899 --> 00:19:54,067
-Nice to meet you, Mike.
-And you.

250
00:19:54,860 --> 00:19:56,236
Thanks for helping.

251
00:19:56,403 --> 00:20:00,199
Well, thank you
for not trying to do this all by yourself.

252
00:20:34,900 --> 00:20:36,902
Hey, Carl?

253
00:20:37,069 --> 00:20:38,362
Yeah?

254
00:20:39,071 --> 00:20:41,698
Hold the fort for a few minutes, would you?

255
00:20:41,865 --> 00:20:43,575
You got it, Mike.

256
00:20:46,828 --> 00:20:49,039
[BASEBALL FANFARE
PLAYING ON ELECTRONIC GAME]

257
00:20:56,213 --> 00:20:57,381
Oh, hey.

258
00:20:59,341 --> 00:21:02,636
-You're here.
-This your idea of stealth?

259
00:21:03,095 --> 00:21:05,389
I never claimed to be good at this.
Any of it.

260
00:21:05,847 --> 00:21:07,266
On that, we can agree.

261
00:21:07,432 --> 00:21:09,726
Yeah, I know. That's why I'm here.

262
00:21:09,893 --> 00:21:11,812
I wanna hire you again.

263
00:21:11,979 --> 00:21:13,689
-Do what now?
-Hire you.

264
00:21:13,855 --> 00:21:16,984
As my backup man. Same terms as before.

265
00:21:17,150 --> 00:21:19,528
I don't wanna make the same mistake
as last time.

266
00:21:19,695 --> 00:21:21,613
You don't wanna make the same mistake...

267
00:21:21,780 --> 00:21:25,284
...then don't get involved with
whatever it is you're getting involved with.

268
00:21:25,492 --> 00:21:28,578
But I'm involved already.

269
00:21:28,787 --> 00:21:30,706
I'm not.

270
00:21:33,250 --> 00:21:35,460
It's Nacho Varga.

271
00:21:43,677 --> 00:21:45,095
What about him?

272
00:21:45,262 --> 00:21:46,763
He broke into my house.

273
00:21:46,930 --> 00:21:48,682
He was inside waiting for me.

274
00:21:48,849 --> 00:21:51,268
Somehow, he got past my security system.

275
00:21:51,435 --> 00:21:52,894
I have no idea how.

276
00:21:53,437 --> 00:21:56,023
All he had to do was unplug your phone lines.

277
00:21:56,481 --> 00:21:59,776
Oh. That's it? Huh.

278
00:22:00,360 --> 00:22:02,237
-What did he want?
-Pills.

279
00:22:02,404 --> 00:22:04,323
Well, not exactly.

280
00:22:04,489 --> 00:22:06,575
Empty Lydristel capsules.

281
00:22:06,992 --> 00:22:10,620
-Lydristel?
-Yeah, they're like nitroglycerin.

282
00:22:10,787 --> 00:22:11,997
And he offered me money.

283
00:22:12,205 --> 00:22:13,957
I mean, lots of money.

284
00:22:14,124 --> 00:22:16,710
Way more than they're even worth...

285
00:22:16,877 --> 00:22:18,170
...but...

286
00:22:18,337 --> 00:22:20,547
...I'm afraid if I don't do it...

287
00:22:20,714 --> 00:22:22,883
...or even if I do do it...

288
00:22:23,717 --> 00:22:24,843
...I don't know.

289
00:22:25,594 --> 00:22:28,889
-Tell him you can't get what he needs.
-I already ordered them.

290
00:22:29,097 --> 00:22:31,683
I mean, the shipment gets here in two days.
He knows.

291
00:22:31,892 --> 00:22:33,310
Then make up an excuse.

292
00:22:35,520 --> 00:22:36,938
Fine. Three thousand.

293
00:22:37,773 --> 00:22:39,816
-I'll give you 3000.
-I'm not interested.

294
00:22:39,983 --> 00:22:42,069
And you, find a way out of it.

295
00:22:42,944 --> 00:22:45,614
-But--
-Not interested.

296
00:23:36,915 --> 00:23:40,043
[ALARM BEEPING]

297
00:23:40,252 --> 00:23:42,087
PAIGE:
<i>Look, full disclosure...</i>

298
00:23:42,254 --> 00:23:46,216
...when you told us about the disciplinary
hearing, I admit it, I had concerns.

299
00:23:46,383 --> 00:23:48,552
Just so you know,
I had to do my due diligence.

300
00:23:48,718 --> 00:23:50,428
I read the transcripts.

301
00:23:50,595 --> 00:23:51,888
All of them.

302
00:23:52,055 --> 00:23:53,140
It was amazing.

303
00:23:53,348 --> 00:23:56,768
What you did to Charles,
you and James set him up perfectly.

304
00:23:56,977 --> 00:23:59,271
You destroyed him.

305
00:23:59,729 --> 00:24:02,357
Oh, my God. I couldn't believe some of it.

306
00:24:02,524 --> 00:24:05,986
"I'm not crazy.
It's 1216, one after Magna Carta."

307
00:24:06,153 --> 00:24:08,655
-The Magna Carta?
-Mm.

308
00:24:08,864 --> 00:24:10,824
PAIGE:
It was perfect.

309
00:24:10,991 --> 00:24:13,994
"You think this chicanery is bad?"

310
00:24:14,286 --> 00:24:16,454
Who talks like that?

311
00:24:16,621 --> 00:24:21,835
On page five is a breakdown
of loan-to-deposit ratios by county...

312
00:24:22,002 --> 00:24:25,130
...and you can see, if Mesa Verde's
gonna comply with section 109...

313
00:24:25,297 --> 00:24:27,340
-...you will have to raise your loan numbers.
-Mm.

314
00:24:27,507 --> 00:24:29,092
That can't be right.

315
00:24:29,259 --> 00:24:30,760
We were fine in Arizona.

316
00:24:31,595 --> 00:24:35,473
Yes, but the FDIC requirements
in Utah are different.

317
00:24:35,682 --> 00:24:39,269
Ninety-six percent? Is it really that high?

318
00:24:39,769 --> 00:24:41,438
I thought Arizona was only 79.

319
00:24:43,064 --> 00:24:47,777
Again, it was,
but Utah has a higher loan-to-deposit ratio.

320
00:24:50,906 --> 00:24:54,409
I think we're gonna need to check that.
That number seems way off.

321
00:24:54,576 --> 00:24:56,286
The numbers are right.

322
00:24:56,661 --> 00:25:00,248
But you can review the guidelines
if you want. Right here.

323
00:25:03,501 --> 00:25:06,379
Are you gonna check them,
or can we move on?

324
00:25:09,883 --> 00:25:11,426
Uh....

325
00:25:13,678 --> 00:25:15,096
No.

326
00:25:15,889 --> 00:25:19,059
Of course, if it's 96, it's 96.

327
00:25:19,809 --> 00:25:21,895
We'll increase our loan numbers.

328
00:25:22,062 --> 00:25:23,688
Absolutely.

329
00:25:26,316 --> 00:25:29,736
Can we review these
fixed-mortgage rates because that's...

330
00:25:29,903 --> 00:25:33,823
-...definitely an area we'll need to focus--
-Paige, I'm s-- That was...

331
00:25:35,158 --> 00:25:36,993
...unprofessional.

332
00:25:37,160 --> 00:25:38,995
I didn't mean to speak to you that way.

333
00:25:39,162 --> 00:25:40,580
Kim...

334
00:25:41,164 --> 00:25:43,500
...don't worry. It's not a problem.

335
00:25:43,667 --> 00:25:44,960
-At all.
-No, I'm sorry.

336
00:25:45,126 --> 00:25:47,545
There's no excuse
for talking to you like that.

337
00:25:49,506 --> 00:25:52,008
I know how hard you've been working on this.

338
00:25:52,634 --> 00:25:55,845
Please, I've forgotten about it already.
You should too.

339
00:25:56,012 --> 00:25:57,430
Okay?

340
00:26:07,649 --> 00:26:10,277
As far as I'm concerned, all we did--

341
00:26:13,154 --> 00:26:15,865
All we did was tear down a sick man.

342
00:26:26,459 --> 00:26:28,878
Fixed-mortgage rates.

343
00:26:29,045 --> 00:26:31,131
I think it's page three.

344
00:26:31,298 --> 00:26:32,674
-Yes.
-Yeah.

345
00:26:34,217 --> 00:26:37,929
There's an acquisition comparison at the top.
And you wanna go by total--

346
00:26:45,895 --> 00:26:47,314
[♪♪♪]

347
00:27:05,707 --> 00:27:06,916
[TIRES SCREECHING]

348
00:27:12,922 --> 00:27:14,341
Get in.

349
00:27:14,507 --> 00:27:17,510
Let's go. Chop-chop. Come on, come on.

350
00:27:41,242 --> 00:27:42,369
Get in.

351
00:27:42,577 --> 00:27:44,079
I'm trying.

352
00:27:46,456 --> 00:27:47,999
[ENGINE SPUTTERING]

353
00:27:48,583 --> 00:27:51,753
-That doesn't sound good.
-Come on, come on.

354
00:27:52,796 --> 00:27:54,422
-Think you're flooding it.
-I'm not.

355
00:27:54,589 --> 00:27:55,715
You're over-cranking it.

356
00:27:55,882 --> 00:27:57,759
You don't know what you're talking about.

357
00:27:57,842 --> 00:28:00,095
We're getting paid
whether we get there or not.

358
00:28:00,261 --> 00:28:02,639
-Maybe we should catch the bus.
-Come on. Just--

359
00:28:02,806 --> 00:28:04,557
It's gonna start, okay?

360
00:28:05,475 --> 00:28:08,186
-You've definitely flooded it.
-He drained the battery.

361
00:28:08,353 --> 00:28:11,147
Can you not talk about something
you know nothing about?

362
00:28:11,314 --> 00:28:13,066
-There's a bus we can get in.
-Shh!

363
00:28:13,233 --> 00:28:15,735
I just need to think for one minute.

364
00:28:15,944 --> 00:28:17,320
[SIGHS]

365
00:28:18,530 --> 00:28:20,824
-We're taking the bus.
-Yeah.

366
00:28:31,084 --> 00:28:32,544
JIMMY:
Film crew.

367
00:28:32,710 --> 00:28:33,920
Hold up the bus.

368
00:28:36,256 --> 00:28:39,300
You see that? Fender Stratocaster
signed by Ritchie Blackmore.

369
00:28:39,467 --> 00:28:42,470
-You know who that is, right?
-Someone no one's ever heard of.

370
00:28:43,054 --> 00:28:47,642
That's real good. I hope your parents enjoy
supporting you for the rest of their lives.

371
00:28:47,809 --> 00:28:51,229
Come on. Ritchie Blackmore. Deep Purple.

372
00:28:52,439 --> 00:28:54,190
"Another Brick in the Wall."

373
00:28:54,649 --> 00:28:57,277
Oh, I weep for the future.

374
00:28:58,111 --> 00:28:59,112
Mr. McGill?

375
00:28:59,654 --> 00:29:00,739
We have a problem.

376
00:29:01,823 --> 00:29:03,032
Them.

377
00:29:05,368 --> 00:29:06,745
Hey, fellas. You ready?

378
00:29:06,911 --> 00:29:10,039
We got the first shot all lined up.
Can I walk you through it?

379
00:29:10,832 --> 00:29:11,833
We hate to do this to you.

380
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:13,710
-We're having second thoughts.
-Yeah.

381
00:29:13,877 --> 00:29:15,837
I get it. That's nerves. Stage fright.

382
00:29:16,045 --> 00:29:18,173
I tell you what. We got cue cards.

383
00:29:18,339 --> 00:29:21,718
And with the magic of editing,
we're gonna make you guys look like...

384
00:29:21,885 --> 00:29:24,971
-...James Garner and Mariette Hartley.
-It's not that.

385
00:29:25,138 --> 00:29:27,515
It's just that it seems like too much money--

386
00:29:27,682 --> 00:29:29,058
For not a whole lot of return.

387
00:29:29,267 --> 00:29:32,771
And that, my friends, that is where
you're mistaken because this is about...

388
00:29:32,937 --> 00:29:34,147
...brand-awareness.

389
00:29:34,314 --> 00:29:38,943
From now on, when people think guitars,
they're gonna think ABQ In Tune.

390
00:29:39,110 --> 00:29:42,071
When they think pianos, ABQ In Tune.

391
00:29:42,238 --> 00:29:46,951
Drums, xylophones, for less than the price of
that Ritchie Blackmore beauty on that rack...

392
00:29:47,118 --> 00:29:49,954
...you're gonna have the whole town thinking,
"ABQ In Tune."

393
00:29:50,121 --> 00:29:51,831
Yeah, but what about the time slot?

394
00:29:51,998 --> 00:29:54,083
-I mean, <i>Murder, She Wrote </i>repeats?
-Come on.

395
00:29:54,542 --> 00:29:55,543
Hey.

396
00:29:55,710 --> 00:30:00,548
Grandmas love buying the gift of music
for little Johnny and Sally and Skip.

397
00:30:00,715 --> 00:30:04,803
And it's school-recital season, so where
are the kids gonna get those recorders?

398
00:30:05,345 --> 00:30:08,473
-We don't sell recorders.
-Synthesizers, then.

399
00:30:08,640 --> 00:30:12,227
But point is, those social-security checks,
they gotta be spent somewhere.

400
00:30:13,978 --> 00:30:15,063
Hey, uh. Ahem.

401
00:30:15,230 --> 00:30:19,818
As it happens, today only,
I can offer the same package...

402
00:30:19,984 --> 00:30:22,904
...but 50 percent off.

403
00:30:25,615 --> 00:30:26,699
Look.

404
00:30:26,866 --> 00:30:28,993
I'm sorry, but we can't. Not today, guys.

405
00:30:30,161 --> 00:30:31,871
Don't do that. Guys. Now come on.

406
00:30:32,080 --> 00:30:34,040
Look, I know you want this. I know you do.

407
00:30:34,207 --> 00:30:36,084
-Fifty percent off.
MAN 1: Yeah, we get it.

408
00:30:36,251 --> 00:30:38,461
But we're just not....

409
00:30:38,628 --> 00:30:40,129
MAN 2:
Convinced.

410
00:30:43,508 --> 00:30:44,843
Free.

411
00:30:45,176 --> 00:30:47,220
I'll shoot the spot for free.

412
00:30:48,930 --> 00:30:50,056
For free?

413
00:30:50,223 --> 00:30:52,225
You will shoot this spot for free?

414
00:30:52,433 --> 00:30:55,311
I'll film your ad,
and I'll put it on the air.

415
00:30:55,478 --> 00:30:59,440
But when you see more traffic
coming through here, and you will...

416
00:30:59,607 --> 00:31:03,403
...then we do the other spots
for the original rate.

417
00:31:03,570 --> 00:31:05,154
Okay? Now how can you say "no"?

418
00:31:06,322 --> 00:31:08,825
-I mean, when we puts it like that.
-I guess we can't.

419
00:31:09,033 --> 00:31:10,326
Good.

420
00:31:10,493 --> 00:31:14,038
That's the best decision you're gonna make.
The best.

421
00:31:52,785 --> 00:31:54,871
You're gonna catch the bus, Mr. McGill?

422
00:31:56,039 --> 00:31:57,707
No, I--

423
00:31:58,207 --> 00:32:00,793
You guys get to the editing room.

424
00:32:00,960 --> 00:32:02,754
I just need...

425
00:32:03,713 --> 00:32:05,298
...to sit.

426
00:32:22,106 --> 00:32:24,025
Mr. McGill.

427
00:32:25,443 --> 00:32:27,779
No. I-- I can't.

428
00:32:27,946 --> 00:32:29,030
It's okay.

429
00:32:30,740 --> 00:32:33,743
That's yours. You earned it.

430
00:32:34,953 --> 00:32:36,788
But you're losing money.

431
00:32:37,664 --> 00:32:39,123
We'll see.

432
00:32:39,374 --> 00:32:41,459
It'll be fine.

433
00:32:43,169 --> 00:32:44,671
Okay.

434
00:32:56,057 --> 00:32:59,602
So I finally got my act together.

435
00:33:00,520 --> 00:33:04,107
I pulled a bunch of Alan's boxes
out of the closet.

436
00:33:05,400 --> 00:33:07,735
Only took me eight years.

437
00:33:11,114 --> 00:33:16,869
I gave all of Alan's clothes a last wash
before driving them over to Goodwill.

438
00:33:19,205 --> 00:33:20,790
I cried.

439
00:33:20,957 --> 00:33:24,377
I cried when I washed them.
I cried when I folded them.

440
00:33:24,544 --> 00:33:26,713
I cried when I dropped them off.

441
00:33:28,715 --> 00:33:30,717
But once it was done...

442
00:33:31,843 --> 00:33:33,469
...it felt good...

443
00:33:34,512 --> 00:33:36,139
...to let them go.

444
00:33:38,391 --> 00:33:40,393
I kept his uniform though. Heh.

445
00:33:40,977 --> 00:33:42,186
Can't let that go.

446
00:33:42,353 --> 00:33:45,398
Lord, he'd never forgive me if I let that go.
Heh, heh.

447
00:33:48,276 --> 00:33:51,154
But I figure it's okay
to keep one thing, right?

448
00:33:51,571 --> 00:33:52,822
I mean...

449
00:33:53,823 --> 00:33:56,743
...people can use the other clothes...

450
00:33:57,910 --> 00:34:00,788
...but I'm not sure what use
they'd have for an old uniform.

451
00:34:05,752 --> 00:34:09,047
I just don't remember
this much homework when I was Kaylee's age.

452
00:34:09,213 --> 00:34:12,341
It doesn't seem to bother her, but still.

453
00:34:12,508 --> 00:34:14,886
Most of it is just busywork.

454
00:34:15,261 --> 00:34:18,181
A couple of us
actually spoke to the school board...

455
00:34:18,347 --> 00:34:19,432
...and they agreed.

456
00:34:19,599 --> 00:34:21,601
Done. All yours.

457
00:34:21,768 --> 00:34:24,395
-Fair warning. The coffee's not all that.
-Hmm.

458
00:34:25,563 --> 00:34:28,524
I guess they feel if you can face this,
you can face anything.

459
00:34:28,691 --> 00:34:32,445
-Could be. I must be stronger than I think.
-Mm.

460
00:34:33,613 --> 00:34:36,240
You mind if I ask?
I really don't mean to pry, but--

461
00:34:36,407 --> 00:34:40,411
Let me guess. You have another
construction job you need my help on.

462
00:34:40,578 --> 00:34:44,373
No. But if I do,
you'll be the first person I call.

463
00:34:44,540 --> 00:34:46,709
Okay. Ask away.

464
00:34:48,086 --> 00:34:50,880
You said you kept your husband's uniform.

465
00:34:51,297 --> 00:34:52,965
Was he on the job?

466
00:34:53,132 --> 00:34:54,967
"On the job"?

467
00:34:55,134 --> 00:34:57,136
Oh, you mean, the police?

468
00:34:57,512 --> 00:34:58,721
No.

469
00:34:58,888 --> 00:35:00,306
Alan was a Navy man.

470
00:35:00,515 --> 00:35:02,767
He was well out of the service
when I lost him.

471
00:35:04,310 --> 00:35:05,353
I'm sorry.

472
00:35:05,520 --> 00:35:07,563
The group has heard my story over and over.

473
00:35:08,397 --> 00:35:10,817
Well, that's what we're here for.

474
00:35:15,321 --> 00:35:16,739
Well...

475
00:35:17,031 --> 00:35:19,450
...Alan loved to hike.

476
00:35:19,617 --> 00:35:22,120
We even opened a camping-supply store.

477
00:35:22,286 --> 00:35:24,705
I helped him with the mail-order side of it.

478
00:35:25,289 --> 00:35:26,999
And then...

479
00:35:28,334 --> 00:35:30,419
...this was eight years ago.

480
00:35:31,045 --> 00:35:33,131
He went hiking in Gila National...

481
00:35:33,339 --> 00:35:35,550
...and never came back.

482
00:35:35,716 --> 00:35:37,260
They found our car...

483
00:35:37,426 --> 00:35:39,428
...but they never found him.

484
00:35:39,971 --> 00:35:41,848
And I don't know if...

485
00:35:42,014 --> 00:35:44,058
...he slipped and fell
or had a heart attack...

486
00:35:44,225 --> 00:35:46,519
...or met someone
who didn't like the way he looked.

487
00:35:47,687 --> 00:35:49,230
I don't know.

488
00:35:49,397 --> 00:35:51,816
And even after all these years...

489
00:35:52,358 --> 00:35:54,360
...not knowing how he passed...

490
00:35:54,569 --> 00:35:56,529
...or where he is...

491
00:36:00,324 --> 00:36:02,410
...I wish it didn't matter.

492
00:36:02,785 --> 00:36:04,370
But it does.

493
00:36:27,894 --> 00:36:29,604
[PHONE DIALING]

494
00:36:37,862 --> 00:36:39,071
PRYCE:
<i>Hello?</i>

495
00:36:40,072 --> 00:36:41,699
It's me.

496
00:36:41,866 --> 00:36:43,701
You make the deal?

497
00:36:44,243 --> 00:36:47,788
<i>Uh, no. Not yet.</i>

498
00:36:48,497 --> 00:36:49,498
<i>Why?</i>

499
00:36:51,042 --> 00:36:52,585
I'm in.

500
00:37:13,689 --> 00:37:15,233
[JIMMY SIGHS]

501
00:37:42,385 --> 00:37:44,470
Hey, let's get out of here.

502
00:37:45,263 --> 00:37:47,515
What? Get out where?

503
00:37:47,682 --> 00:37:50,017
I'm up to my neck in Mesa Verde. I can't.

504
00:37:51,227 --> 00:37:54,230
-Come on, we're going. Up.
-No, I can't.

505
00:37:54,397 --> 00:37:55,898
Nope. Nothing.

506
00:37:56,065 --> 00:37:58,526
Nothing you can do to stop this.

507
00:37:58,859 --> 00:38:01,988
Oh, one thing. You have to drive.

508
00:38:02,655 --> 00:38:05,574
Oh, oh, oh. Look at this guy.

509
00:38:05,741 --> 00:38:07,076
[DANCE MUSIC
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

510
00:38:07,785 --> 00:38:09,870
It's Alfred Hitchcock in a rented toupee.

511
00:38:10,079 --> 00:38:11,163
[KIM CHUCKLING]

512
00:38:11,372 --> 00:38:13,499
KIM: Come on.
Why would you rent a toupee?

513
00:38:13,666 --> 00:38:15,293
JIMMY: You know, from the toupee store...

514
00:38:15,459 --> 00:38:17,878
...so you don't have to maintain it.

515
00:38:20,339 --> 00:38:22,883
SERVER: All right. Seven and seven.
-Yeah.

516
00:38:23,050 --> 00:38:26,304
-And an old fashioned.
-Keep them coming, good sir.

517
00:38:26,512 --> 00:38:27,805
Uh, oh. Ahem.

518
00:38:28,014 --> 00:38:31,684
Can you... start charging this card
instead of that other one?

519
00:38:31,851 --> 00:38:32,685
Yeah. You got it.

520
00:38:32,852 --> 00:38:34,520
JIMMY: Thank you.
-No problem.

521
00:38:34,979 --> 00:38:37,815
You're not maxing out your cards, are you?

522
00:38:37,982 --> 00:38:39,442
Of course not.

523
00:38:39,984 --> 00:38:42,695
I'm, uh, spreading the points around.

524
00:38:42,862 --> 00:38:44,697
-I got a system.
-Oh.

525
00:38:46,198 --> 00:38:49,368
That moron takes the bet.

526
00:38:49,535 --> 00:38:50,786
He took three points.

527
00:38:50,953 --> 00:38:52,288
He's a fool. Look.

528
00:38:52,788 --> 00:38:56,959
-Is it wrong?
-Wait, this guy over here.

529
00:38:57,960 --> 00:39:00,963
Yeah. He wants everyone
to know what a big spender he is.

530
00:39:01,172 --> 00:39:04,759
I've got every dollar that guy owns.

531
00:39:04,925 --> 00:39:07,345
We're here to meet a celebrity...

532
00:39:07,511 --> 00:39:09,138
...who's donating to my charity.

533
00:39:09,347 --> 00:39:11,057
Kevin Costner.

534
00:39:11,223 --> 00:39:13,351
I will go stand in that corner...

535
00:39:13,517 --> 00:39:15,353
...you point me out.

536
00:39:15,519 --> 00:39:17,646
You're meeting Kevin Costner.

537
00:39:17,813 --> 00:39:19,940
What? You don't look like Kevin Costner.

538
00:39:20,149 --> 00:39:22,193
I look exactly like Kevin Costner.

539
00:39:22,360 --> 00:39:26,030
People are always coming up to me,
saying they love me in <i>Bull Durham.</i>

540
00:39:26,197 --> 00:39:27,323
Never.

541
00:39:27,490 --> 00:39:28,908
-Never happened.
-Always.

542
00:39:29,075 --> 00:39:30,409
-Hey, hey. You.
-Not that one.

543
00:39:30,576 --> 00:39:32,578
SERVER: Yes, sir.
-What is this?

544
00:39:32,745 --> 00:39:36,582
-Uh, dirty martini?
-No, this is a $14 glass of puke.

545
00:39:36,874 --> 00:39:40,211
Why don't you get that idiot look
off your face and get me another one?

546
00:39:40,378 --> 00:39:41,921
-That guy.
MAN: Who said anything about gin?

547
00:39:42,088 --> 00:39:45,299
-How do we get him?
MAN: Well, I want vodka.

548
00:39:45,758 --> 00:39:48,594
-What, am I just gonna hold it here?
-What do you think?

549
00:39:48,761 --> 00:39:50,846
MAN: You go and get me another one.
-The--

550
00:39:51,013 --> 00:39:54,225
-The trick with the coin you told me about.
MAN: I know your boss. I'm an investor here.

551
00:39:54,392 --> 00:39:56,560
-Or the counterfeit bill?
-No.

552
00:39:57,520 --> 00:39:58,813
That guy's a real asshole.

553
00:39:58,979 --> 00:40:00,981
--act together and get me a real drink.

554
00:40:01,148 --> 00:40:02,525
JIMMY:
He needs to go down hard.

555
00:40:02,691 --> 00:40:04,777
What kind of menial job is this?

556
00:40:06,570 --> 00:40:08,155
Here's what we're gonna do.

557
00:40:08,322 --> 00:40:12,368
We're gonna sell him
a worthless credit card for 5000 bucks.

558
00:40:13,786 --> 00:40:15,579
Here's what you do.

559
00:40:16,038 --> 00:40:18,624
Make eye contact with him.

560
00:40:18,791 --> 00:40:21,585
It's all it will take for him
to think you're interested.

561
00:40:21,752 --> 00:40:26,257
I'll act good and drunk, and he'll think
I'm a loser and try to steal you away.

562
00:40:26,882 --> 00:40:29,844
He will persist.

563
00:40:31,470 --> 00:40:34,014
You tell him you can't leave me. Not yet.

564
00:40:34,181 --> 00:40:36,559
Let him know you're trying to roll me.

565
00:40:36,725 --> 00:40:38,519
He'll want in.

566
00:40:38,811 --> 00:40:41,105
He'll help you ply me with booze.

567
00:40:41,272 --> 00:40:43,524
Then you take my wallet, you lift the card.

568
00:40:43,941 --> 00:40:45,651
Following this?

569
00:40:47,153 --> 00:40:49,613
We're not actually doing this, right?

570
00:40:50,364 --> 00:40:51,740
We're just talking.

571
00:40:54,869 --> 00:40:56,328
Yeah.

572
00:40:57,037 --> 00:40:58,831
Just talking.

573
00:41:05,588 --> 00:41:06,881
What--?

574
00:41:09,758 --> 00:41:11,135
Nothing.

575
00:41:11,635 --> 00:41:14,847
-It's not nothing. What?
-I keep thinking....

576
00:41:17,933 --> 00:41:19,477
Was there another way?

577
00:41:20,895 --> 00:41:22,563
"Another way"?

578
00:41:24,231 --> 00:41:26,442
Chuck? Is that what you're talking about?

579
00:41:26,609 --> 00:41:27,860
Kim.

580
00:41:28,194 --> 00:41:31,780
He had us in a corner. Okay?
We did what we had to do.

581
00:41:31,989 --> 00:41:33,532
-But Rebecca--
-Everything...

582
00:41:34,200 --> 00:41:36,619
...that happened was his own fault.

583
00:41:36,785 --> 00:41:37,661
Everything.

584
00:41:37,828 --> 00:41:39,788
You put him in the rearview mirror.

585
00:41:39,955 --> 00:41:42,666
He is not worth thinking about. Done.

586
00:41:48,964 --> 00:41:50,424
SERVER 2:
Why, thank you.

587
00:41:50,591 --> 00:41:51,675
Have a good evening.

588
00:41:51,842 --> 00:41:54,136
Can I get anybody anything else?

589
00:42:08,859 --> 00:42:10,444
How about that one?

590
00:42:15,157 --> 00:42:19,078
I bet we could get him to invest...

591
00:42:19,286 --> 00:42:22,623
...in some of Giselle Saint Claire's
land in South Africa.

592
00:42:22,790 --> 00:42:23,958
Oh, yeah.

593
00:42:24,124 --> 00:42:25,751
Definitely.

594
00:42:26,627 --> 00:42:29,171
Mining rights would be all his.

595
00:43:04,456 --> 00:43:05,791
Really?

596
00:43:06,375 --> 00:43:07,501
He called me.

597
00:43:07,710 --> 00:43:09,003
For obvious reasons.

598
00:43:09,169 --> 00:43:11,547
Look, I'm not here to rip him off.

599
00:43:11,714 --> 00:43:13,465
He has the stuff, right?

600
00:43:14,174 --> 00:43:16,802
I need to know what you're planning.

601
00:43:17,011 --> 00:43:19,179
What's it matter to you?

602
00:43:19,346 --> 00:43:22,308
I know they're for Salamanca. Nitro pills.

603
00:43:22,474 --> 00:43:23,976
Your boss has heart problems.

604
00:43:24,768 --> 00:43:27,855
You already got it all figured out.
Why are you asking?

605
00:43:28,480 --> 00:43:30,774
How you gonna make the switch?

606
00:43:32,610 --> 00:43:33,652
[SIGHS]

607
00:43:33,861 --> 00:43:35,821
Hector keeps the pills in his coat pocket.

608
00:43:35,904 --> 00:43:38,240
When he hangs up his coat,
I'll make the switch.

609
00:43:39,533 --> 00:43:42,036
Mm. He goes down, then what?

610
00:43:42,995 --> 00:43:45,331
His heart goes out. That's it.

611
00:43:45,497 --> 00:43:47,207
MIKE:
A lot of eyes on Salamanca.

612
00:43:47,541 --> 00:43:48,917
You do this...

613
00:43:49,084 --> 00:43:52,379
...how are you gonna stop them
from finding out it was you?

614
00:43:54,423 --> 00:43:56,342
Are you trying to tell me not to do this?

615
00:43:56,550 --> 00:43:58,761
I'm not telling you anything.

616
00:43:58,927 --> 00:44:01,555
I just wanna make sure
you know what you're getting into.

617
00:44:01,722 --> 00:44:04,767
I'm not getting into anything. I'm in it.

618
00:44:04,933 --> 00:44:06,894
I've got no choice.

619
00:44:11,357 --> 00:44:13,359
Hector wants to use my dad's business.

620
00:44:13,567 --> 00:44:17,071
My dad is a straight arrow.
He won't stand for it, which means...

621
00:44:17,237 --> 00:44:21,116
...he goes to the police,
which means he's a dead man.

622
00:44:22,076 --> 00:44:23,869
And that's not happening.

623
00:44:24,495 --> 00:44:26,914
You get caught, it could get worse.

624
00:44:27,122 --> 00:44:29,249
You don't think I know who I'm dealing with?

625
00:44:29,416 --> 00:44:30,834
MIKE:
No.

626
00:44:31,126 --> 00:44:32,544
I don't.

627
00:44:50,604 --> 00:44:52,439
What are you doing?

628
00:45:12,793 --> 00:45:16,213
There are more people than the Salamancas
to worry about here.

629
00:45:16,839 --> 00:45:20,759
Now, if you manage to pull this off
without a bullet in your head...

630
00:45:20,926 --> 00:45:22,761
...and switch those pills...

631
00:45:22,928 --> 00:45:24,263
...then switch them back.

632
00:45:26,515 --> 00:45:28,434
Switch them back?

633
00:45:28,600 --> 00:45:29,643
Why?

634
00:45:29,810 --> 00:45:32,521
If anyone gets an itch
about the medicine not working...

635
00:45:32,688 --> 00:45:34,857
...they're gonna look at those pills.

636
00:45:35,023 --> 00:45:38,026
You do this, switch them back.

637
00:45:43,365 --> 00:45:44,450
So...

638
00:45:44,658 --> 00:45:47,870
-...you're gonna let us make this deal?
-You got the money?

639
00:45:50,372 --> 00:45:51,748
Good.

640
00:45:53,417 --> 00:45:55,878
Now before we do this...

641
00:45:56,044 --> 00:45:58,172
...I'm gonna need one more thing from you.

642
00:46:05,596 --> 00:46:07,181
[INTERCOM BEEPS]

643
00:46:08,390 --> 00:46:09,600
Yes.

644
00:46:10,350 --> 00:46:11,560
Okay.

645
00:46:12,186 --> 00:46:14,396
Miss Valco will see you now.

646
00:46:15,355 --> 00:46:16,982
Second door.

647
00:46:25,157 --> 00:46:26,783
Hey there. Come on in.

648
00:46:26,950 --> 00:46:30,913
Yeah. Hi. I've called quite a few times...

649
00:46:31,079 --> 00:46:33,707
...about an issue I'm trying to address.

650
00:46:33,874 --> 00:46:35,918
Do you have your policy number?

651
00:46:36,418 --> 00:46:38,003
No.

652
00:46:38,504 --> 00:46:40,506
Can you just look up my name? McGill.

653
00:46:46,303 --> 00:46:49,515
Charles McGill of Hamlin Hamlin McGill?

654
00:46:50,474 --> 00:46:52,601
No, that's my brother. Um....

655
00:46:53,519 --> 00:46:54,728
I'm Jimmy.

656
00:46:54,895 --> 00:46:57,940
James McGill. Solo practitioner.

657
00:46:58,565 --> 00:46:59,566
Ah.

658
00:46:59,775 --> 00:47:03,195
There you are. Looks like you're all paid up
through the year.

659
00:47:03,362 --> 00:47:04,905
That's sort of the issue.

660
00:47:05,113 --> 00:47:08,700
Long story short.
Through a series of unfortunate events...

661
00:47:08,867 --> 00:47:11,036
...my license has been suspended.

662
00:47:11,203 --> 00:47:13,121
Yes, I see that here.

663
00:47:13,288 --> 00:47:15,958
Right. Well, I was hoping
I could get a refund...

664
00:47:16,124 --> 00:47:17,876
...for the time that I won't be a lawyer.

665
00:47:18,043 --> 00:47:19,753
Now, that's only fair, right?

666
00:47:20,379 --> 00:47:22,965
I'm sorry, Mr. McGill.
It doesn't work like that.

667
00:47:23,131 --> 00:47:26,718
We don't refund
for unused malpractice insurance.

668
00:47:27,427 --> 00:47:32,724
-But it's-- It's a lot of money for nothing.
-I understand it seems that way...

669
00:47:32,891 --> 00:47:36,687
...but if one of your clients decides
they want to bring a suit against you...

670
00:47:36,853 --> 00:47:38,564
...this continues your coverage.

671
00:47:39,565 --> 00:47:43,485
That's the thing. My clients, they love me.

672
00:47:43,652 --> 00:47:46,280
I mean,
they would never bring a suit against me.

673
00:47:46,446 --> 00:47:48,740
I'm extremely lovable.

674
00:47:48,949 --> 00:47:53,495
I can see that,
but it's company policy.

675
00:47:55,247 --> 00:47:57,708
What about we put the insurance on hold?

676
00:47:57,874 --> 00:48:01,295
And then, if someone were to try to sue me,
which they won't...

677
00:48:01,461 --> 00:48:02,879
...then we just...

678
00:48:03,046 --> 00:48:05,173
...kick that old policy back into gear.

679
00:48:05,340 --> 00:48:07,885
I understand your situation. I do.

680
00:48:08,051 --> 00:48:12,014
But there are rules preventing us
from stopping and starting coverage.

681
00:48:12,639 --> 00:48:18,020
And I regret to inform you that
when your license is reinstated next year...

682
00:48:18,186 --> 00:48:21,648
...because of the suspension,
your premiums are going to go up.

683
00:48:22,608 --> 00:48:24,192
Considerably.

684
00:48:25,611 --> 00:48:26,903
How "considerably"?

685
00:48:28,572 --> 00:48:29,698
Um....

686
00:48:33,827 --> 00:48:40,125
Looks like, roughly, 150 percent.

687
00:48:44,463 --> 00:48:46,465
God....

688
00:48:53,930 --> 00:48:55,474
Mr. McGill?

689
00:49:02,481 --> 00:49:04,191
Oh....

690
00:49:05,984 --> 00:49:07,778
Mr. McGill, I'm sorry.

691
00:49:07,945 --> 00:49:10,822
I wish we could help you, but we just can't.

692
00:49:10,989 --> 00:49:12,157
[SNIFFLING]

693
00:49:12,366 --> 00:49:14,159
I'm sorry.

694
00:49:16,078 --> 00:49:17,954
It's hard.

695
00:49:18,580 --> 00:49:20,499
Very, very hard.

696
00:49:21,583 --> 00:49:24,169
I'm just having a rough time.

697
00:49:25,671 --> 00:49:27,714
I just need a break.

698
00:49:27,881 --> 00:49:30,509
Just one break.

699
00:49:32,135 --> 00:49:36,973
And I know--
I know you can't do anything, but...

700
00:49:38,600 --> 00:49:41,103
...I'm getting run out
on this community service...

701
00:49:41,269 --> 00:49:45,816
...and I'm getting ripped off left and right.

702
00:49:46,483 --> 00:49:48,735
And my car won't start.

703
00:49:49,945 --> 00:49:53,073
My gal is disappointed in me, and...

704
00:49:53,573 --> 00:49:55,409
...my brother.

705
00:49:57,911 --> 00:50:00,539
[VOICE BREAKING]
My brother is sick.

706
00:50:01,415 --> 00:50:03,500
And he's alone.

707
00:50:05,711 --> 00:50:07,796
I spent years caring for him...

708
00:50:07,963 --> 00:50:10,549
...and now he hates me.

709
00:50:10,716 --> 00:50:14,553
He's the only family I got left,
and he hates me.

710
00:50:14,720 --> 00:50:16,263
He hates my guts.

711
00:50:17,222 --> 00:50:18,598
Is this your brother Charles?

712
00:50:21,226 --> 00:50:22,811
And I pretend not to care...

713
00:50:22,978 --> 00:50:25,856
...but he's my brother. How can I not?

714
00:50:27,065 --> 00:50:29,025
He's mentally ill.

715
00:50:29,693 --> 00:50:32,571
And he's-- He's holed up in a house
with no electricity.

716
00:50:32,738 --> 00:50:36,241
He's working by the light of gas lanterns.

717
00:50:36,867 --> 00:50:39,995
He's making mistakes
with his clients. He's...

718
00:50:40,203 --> 00:50:42,831
...mixing up numbers on important documents.

719
00:50:42,998 --> 00:50:44,499
He--

720
00:50:45,459 --> 00:50:49,254
He had a complete mental breakdown
at the bar hearing.

721
00:50:49,671 --> 00:50:51,423
Your brother, he had...

722
00:50:51,590 --> 00:50:52,924
...a breakdown in court?

723
00:50:53,467 --> 00:50:55,677
It's in the transcripts.

724
00:50:58,013 --> 00:51:00,515
I'm not worried. I'm just--

725
00:51:00,766 --> 00:51:04,186
If he screws up with one more big client...

726
00:51:05,270 --> 00:51:07,063
...it's just gonna destroy him.

727
00:51:10,567 --> 00:51:11,693
Don't--

728
00:51:11,860 --> 00:51:13,069
Don't write.

729
00:51:13,278 --> 00:51:15,447
What are you writing? No, don't write.

730
00:51:15,614 --> 00:51:17,491
I-- I didn't mean to say that.

731
00:51:17,699 --> 00:51:19,159
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
I don't want him...

732
00:51:19,326 --> 00:51:21,912
...to get in trouble with you guys
because of me.

733
00:51:22,079 --> 00:51:25,749
-Right.
-I'm sorry. I'm gonna go.

734
00:51:26,625 --> 00:51:28,460
You're not gonna do anything, are you?

735
00:51:29,044 --> 00:51:31,463
I-- I wouldn't worry about it, Mr. McGill.

736
00:51:31,630 --> 00:51:33,256
But please feel better.

737
00:51:33,465 --> 00:51:35,467
I'm sorry.

738
00:51:36,551 --> 00:51:38,970
Just-- Forget.

739
00:51:54,569 --> 00:51:56,988
[♪♪♪]
